SIMPLE: equivocate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Equivocate
<hw>E*quiv"o*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Equivocated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Equivocating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>aequivocatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>aequivocari</ets> to be called by
the same name, fr. L. <ets>aequivocus</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧quivoquer</ets>. See <er>Equivocal</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>To use words of equivocal or doubtful
signification; to express one's opinions in terms which admit of
different senses, with intent to deceive; to use ambiguous expressions
with a view to mislead; <as>as, to <ex>equivocate</ex> is the work of
duplicity</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All that Garnet had to say for him was that he supposed he meant
to <qex>equivocate</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Stillingfleet.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To prevaricate; evade; shuffle; quibble. See
<er>Prevaricate</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Equivocate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Equivocate
<hw>E*quiv"o*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To render
equivocal or ambiguous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>equivocated</qex> his vow by a mental reservation.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir G. Buck.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Equivocation</ent>⟦br⟧
